SIMPLE: functional
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Functional
<hw>Func"tion*al</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucr⟧⟦nsm⟧k"sh⟦ucr⟧n*⟦ait⟧l)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or connected with, a
function or duty; official.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Pathology, Physiol.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the
function of an organ or part, or to the functions in general; involving
or affecting function rather than physiology; <as>as,
<ex>functional</ex> deafness; a <ex>functional</ex> disease</as>. See
<cref>functional disease</cref>, below.</def> <wn16s>[wns=2]</wn16s>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Designed for or capable of a particular function or
use; <as>as, a style of writing in which every word is
<ex>functional</ex>; <ex>functional</ex> architecture</as>.</def>
<wn16s>[wns=1]</wn16s>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fit or ready for use or service; useable; in working
order; <as>as, the toaster was still <ex>functional</ex> even after
being dropped; the lawnmower is a bit rusty but still
<ex>functional</ex></as>. Antonym of <ant>out of order</ant> and
<ant>nonfunctional</ant>.</def> <wn16s>[wns=4 & 6]</wn16s>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> usable, useable, in working order(predicate),
operable, operational, running(prenominal), operative.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Designed to emphasize practical utility rather than
artistic or aesthetic purposes; <as>as, <ex>functional</ex> education
selects knowledge that is concrete and usable rather than abstract and
theoretical; <ex>functional</ex> architecture; an amateurish device,
crude but <ex>functional</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Functional disease</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a
disease of which the symptoms cannot be referred to any appreciable
lesion or change of structure; the derangement of an organ arising from
a cause, often unknown, external to itself opposed to <contr>organic
disease</contr>, in which the organ itself is affected.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>functionalism</ent>⟦br⟧
